The Higgs boson scrubbed
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that this is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly certain.
Suppose, however, that it is the Higgs, since the chances of making a mistake seem thin, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this lower world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot end up in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly consisting of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner there are good citizens named fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at any rate, not for this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all beasts as exotic as you might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "light particle" that is the "message" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field at that precise location, much like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" arises an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore, one of the "power-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with this difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that must be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond from which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring in circumference! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between Higgs and mass.
It is not all particles, or all materials, that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold of itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, it is not all particles that interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, hold) do not.
Now, what "can bring" all this research, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancy between the observations and the predictions of the MS.
There are also many who eagerly wish to find them, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and block some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (up!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-up!).
But such gaps have not been found at CERN until now.
Impacts
The repercussions of these researches in the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. All-the-World, they are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
At the beginning of the 1960s, laser pioneers at Bell Laboratories had no suspicion of the revolution that their work would trigger.
They envisioned scientific applications of it, but nothing else.
In fact, the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed), in 1962 - told us already fire, at first the laser was seen rather as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his optical work.
This sensor, although not at all his original intention, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and earned him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, you never know...
Palliative Care - The Best Way to Die... <0x7C> The Duty
With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is expected to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
Much remains to be done in this essential area.
The Duty tried to look at it more closely.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that gnawed him had left him a two-year respite.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven years old," said he, half-fig half-raisin, lying in his bed at the hospice of Victor-Gadbois, of Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even to eat alone.
Attacked in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, talks to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The Courage of Ordinary Death.
“My biggest wish is that I’m cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
"During our lives, we learn that a man pisses standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Regressing to the child’s stage, for some people, is unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the person’s ability to accept regression,” he says.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments unfold at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and stifled".
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
"I don't have any wishes in life anymore," she says, before accepting that she is put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the coming days, however, she expects a last visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provide body care and food assistance.
These are palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, you will agree to provide mouth care for brandy or Pepsi, as required.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died overnight.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as much as we help patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but are not the same.
Alongside an old 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family gathering in the courtyard, well held in his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
“For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” Martel said.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal phase of his or her life, whether at home, hospital or care home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Palliative Home Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that causes several physicians specializing in palliative care to fear the passage of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not performing enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before agreeing to euthanasia.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without doing what was necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients will only ask to die because they do not receive adequate care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are angry with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard’s hopes of survival were already minimal when she gave up on challenging chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was stopping fighting, she said.
Yet she told me I was done!
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for failing to comply with their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are reported to be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to sleeping the patient until his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
