With Bitcoin, pay and sell without the banks
The exact opposite of current currency exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the way of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files peer-to-peer.
Approximately 200,000 transactions have already been recorded thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of $30 in June 2011, fell to $2, five months later, before returning today around about $10 (the prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to global exchanges in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin stands out from other types of virtual currency such as “credits”, used to progress in a video game that is earned by playing or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But, every time, a central authority controls and processes exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all the nodes in the network are both account book custodians, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the way of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner of which, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a phase of file hash, i.e. of transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "cutting" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to fraud, one user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other being orphaned because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to a hundred millionth, leaving some margin.
The difficulty of the challenge is also noted with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposits stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not concern the protocol itself,” said Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payments company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Major actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the book of accounts and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, “giant salaries” were launched.
“Three thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also the author of an educational book on this currency, believes much in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus return cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
They just need to communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who says he has thousands of users.
There is a general movement of questioning hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, in the event of a success of this currency.
We left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the Americans are expected to follow in late 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to retake possession of its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting anything from us.
It is above all the Afghan peasants that we have punished by considering them as terrorists.
And we ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the mutilated.
The Taliban are composed of foreign extremists, former refugee leaders in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the foreign armed presence, as in the Soviet times.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes aided by local insurgents, they will no longer be tolerated when Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the top of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, took place in order.
Convoys of trucks and armored vehicles joined Kabul without being attacked, overflighted by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban raids on Kabul by the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible progress from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country on fire and bloody due to the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghans paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants overwhelmed by the al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved these days.
Former Mujahideen, Afghan government and current Taliban join in a desire to keep women in a lower position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They have turned into businessmen, seizing government lands to sell them into building land to returnees from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge U.S. outsourcing contracts.
They disregarded themselves; most of them did not fight themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have been able to take advantage of American generosities: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
