It will also take some time for Afghanistan and Pakistan, which are largely dependent on imports and exports, to return to normal relations.
The departure of the French fighting troops ended on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aids: high school for girls, boys, French department at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support to the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win the hearts and minds" and to carry out the impossible task of making aid and offensive actions coincide, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), suppressed in 2012, has carried out, and carried out by a small French NGO, many works of collective interest and actions of agricultural rehabilitation.
This work, which was greedy for local labour, was able to help contain the insurrection: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase in arable areas.
What will we leave as a souvenir after two billion euros of military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very hard in these valleys, which are often more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in the province of Kapisa.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurrection led by foreign groups, which the farmers told me they wished, a small, well-controlled civil aid that directly affects them would have to be maintained for them.
A constitution with forceps in Egypt
This is President Mohammed Mursi's new poker shot.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its all.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this House an additional two months to complete its work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusions", continuing to "betray his word" and "trample on the right".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time forced the Brothers to renounce their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as protest rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in favor, as he claimed in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this use of a hasty vote is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I retain full powers", these are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this constituent assembly, the vast majority of whom are Islamists, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, feeling that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacing members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it was most often unanimous votes on the articles.
Commentators were also amused by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, with some members of the committee considering that the constituent's clock was misregulated.
The text, which was still being voted last night, contains 234 articles.
Article 2 remains the same as in the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law."
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a pledge of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” reply the Liberals, who see it as a blow of communication.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to vote are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" temperament Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, eds.].
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are markedly reduced compared to what they were under the former regime.
Another controversial point: the powers conferred on the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the review of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Neither will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as demanded by human rights associations.
They also express their concerns about the text, which they deem liberticidal.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, no article echoes the protection of women, notes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will parade them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has chosen five main reasons to visit Israel.
Go and adore the holy places
Make yourself a must: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptism funds" will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm or where the fishing was miraculous.
It is in this very place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Rue de la Sufferance or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Fortress Antonia (the Pretorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Anointing Stone and the burial.
This is where the Christian center of the world is located, a symbol of the salvation of mankind.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews: the Lamentation Wall which constitutes the remnant of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different denominations leave small words with prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of Masada Fortress, an ancient enemy refuge built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m of altitude, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit all of them during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It exhibits mainly the paintings of the impressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of mouldings of visitors and guardians of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which reviews the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
The three major seaside resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Please note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the water temperature does not fall below 21° while the air temperature can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure water contains brine and very easily holds back swimmers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The surrounding landscapes are of surreal beauty.
It comes to perform a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to cure various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the edge of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to stroll through the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the street walls corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who came to do photo shoots from all over Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera shows.
Note to tourists
If you go to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar equals 3.8 shekels).
When it comes to urban transport, these are mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only subway line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
This is almost an underground funicular.
The trip in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturdays.
From Friday night to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop.
And the work week begins on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, scaleless fish and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
There is a multitude of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no dogs wandering in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-nourished cats that walk the proud air.
You can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These cats love past places and do not refuse to be delighted.
Car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Admission to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who has a language, goes to Moscow": migrants save money to learn the language
As MEPs and human rights activists dispute what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling “fake” certificates have already appeared in the country.
Each year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to make money to help their families stay home.
Since 1 December, a law has come into force that stipulates that each migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
At the moment, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Immigration Service promises, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will need to validate your Russian language skills in order to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained educational certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the University of Peoples' Friendship, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take exams in every city in the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce reviews was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it do?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First, the representatives of the migration service respond, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery to work".
Many are talking about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will torment themselves for months without food and without paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised something, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they are taken their passports, and they do not get the salary they are expected to pay," said Tolib Charipov, head of the Migration Services Directorate for the work of the migration service in Tajikistan.
Don't argue with me, Mr. Policeman!
However, many Central Asian republicans who wish to make money in Russia trust that they not only do not know the language of the country they wish to go to, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families don’t even have enough to feed their children, not to mention dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people go out to make money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will only be for migrants with legal status.
Without statute, there will be no examination or official work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason: administrative barriers and still language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 miles rubles.
And then, one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have fake documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking us for 100, 200 rubles, of what to buy cigarettes, tea," Umed Khoushkadamov, a national of Tajikistan, told reporters.
“Get fast, don’t lose, and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that migrant registration papers were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language exam certificates have already been confiscated by Federal Migration Service employees.
Fake papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not take them for nothing: every migrant who hoped so to facilitate the task of exams had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Representatives of the government and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper pieces".
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the first stroke exam time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian weapon carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it was the shooting during weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to ban the use of rubber bullet weapons in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun permit from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma’s committee for security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the arms law would be introduced to the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is pleased to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a recorded weapon is minimal, said Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168,000 crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are certain that strengthening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, any weapon can be found in Moscow today for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black arms market is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, retired colonel who served ten years in the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking arms commands
The first is "military trace", that is, weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stockpiles and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal guns go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of them have often suffered explosions.
"Verified versions indicate that some fires were deliberately triggered to conceal the deficit," he said.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are for something.
“We see private arms factories that do not compete on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” one expert said.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A large proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," the former military added.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons in the black market.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Public Administration Study.
Experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the army and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "by fault of employees whose work is related to weapons," the report explains.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture, and 5% are from “underground excavations”.
A salesman and consultant at an armoury who asked to remain anonymous asserts that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these underground search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, he says, sellers will pick up new goods from military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT gun.
We deliver it to him by passing the merchandise through a fence.
“He transports it to the city and sells it for €900 per unit with two chargers,” he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a check purchase from illegal arms dealers," the seller added.
