U.S. fast-food and supermarket workers on strike
Nearly a quarter of American teenagers go through a cashier job at McDonald’s
In recent days, a wave of protests has risen against the low wages practiced by Walmart supermarkets and famous fast food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
At the moment, no one can predict whether this wave will increase or shorten quickly.
These actions are supported by unions and a number of left-wing associations.
Alongside the rise in modest wages for basic workers at Walmart and in fast food chains, the organizers of the demonstrations want to see the creation of unions.
This sector is not currently covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
Protests began last week, after Thanksgiving, the “Black Friday,” as a pouring rain of sales grabbing millions of people hit America and sometimes sparked scrambles.
On that day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their positions to organize strike pickets with trade unions and left-wing activists in the company’s stores whose products are intended for consumers of the modest and middle classes.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting guns to car batteries, vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-paid Walmart employees only shop at their workplace.
The price and choice of products have made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell its cheap products due to the low salaries of its employees.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or handheld scanners.
Participants in the "Black Friday" protests demanded an increase in wages, complaining that the price of medical insurance provided by the company had increased from $30 to $100 per month.
For the basic employee at Walmart who gets $9.5 an hour, it’s an amount he can’t afford.
Scientists at Berkley University in California have shown that if Walmart raised the average salary to $12 an hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
That’s 1.1% more than what it currently spends.
If Walmart transferred the entire wage increase to consumers’ shoulders, every run in the store would be 46 cents more.
They will spend only $12.39 more in a year than they do now.
Walmart supporters note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and did not harm the group.
The "Black Friday" continued in the stores from 8 o'clock in the evening to midnight the next day and Walmart sold over that period 5,000 items per second.
His cash registers made a total of 100 million transactions for Black Friday.
Dan Fogleman, a spokesman for the company, said in an interview with the left-wing Huffington Post that “less than five” Walmart employees had left their positions and that the protest was just a “com’ operation among so many others” on the part of the organising union.
"Next client!"
The protests continued this week in New York and were not about Walmart stores either (in this progressive city, they are not very popular, so they are not there yet) but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s advertises selling billions of portions and after they don’t even give you sick leave and don’t pay you for the work you honestly did!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Council Member
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York law is $7.25 an hour.
Fast foods increase over time, but few, on average, its core employees in New York are getting $8.90 an hour.
No one in this city touches them less than they do.
It's inconceivable for me to live with that money in New York.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of American teenagers worked at McDonald’s after high school while living with their parents.
Few people saw it as their main source of income or wanted to stay there for a long time.
Today, I find myself interviewing McDonald's employees who complain that they have to live with this salary and sometimes have to feed their children with it.
On the other hand, there are comments on the Wall Street Journal forum saying that it is irresponsible to make children if you don't know what you're going to feed them with.
Protesters who launched the movement on Thursday at 6.30 a.m. near McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue were demanding that cashiers and fast-food cooks be paid at least $15 an hour, a multiplication more than twice the current minimum wage.
They also called for the creation of unions in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from obstructing and punishing union protesters with bullying or layoffs.
However, administration rarely simplifies their lives.
For a trade union, seizing fast food remains a difficult task, and for concrete reasons.
One of the main ones is the extraordinary rotation of staff.
They disagree
Other tumultuous protests were held near several other fast food chains.
The highlight of the protest was the midday rally near McDonald's in Times Square with the intervention of several local Democratic politicians, including that of City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said: "McDonald's announcement sells billions of portions and after they don't even give you sick leave and don't pay you for the work you honestly did!"
The protesters were supported by other prominent New York Democrats, including Mayor Bill De Blasio who said that "we must all support fast food workers so that they get a fair salary and the economic well-being that every New Yorker deserves.
The New York Times characterized the event as the most important event the fast food sector has ever seen in its entire history.
But only a few hundred people participated in it, not to mention that not all were fast food workers, who employ tens of thousands of people in New York.
It is difficult for now to say whether this spark of mass movement will make small.
"At the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain."
Recently, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to seeing augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, it was Google that unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November it was learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it is clear from the interview with the director of the group of interactive 3D technologies of the Microsoft lab in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, that for the scientists of this company, the glasses are already ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands, by the creation of open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We work on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time try to broaden the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has remained for the moment to the pixels on flat screen and sometimes to the touch.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead of us and guess the radical changes that will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox sells today without Kinect because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What does the future hold for us as well?
- Although the Kinect has rendered the physical interaction, a lot of things take place on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information input has been improved (the system receives more data), but performance, for now, not really.
We’re trying to change that and we’re working on real 3D imaging systems running on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to get the computer world out into ours, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space that surrounds it.
Thus, we will be able to complete the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And to begin with, let’s get rid of these stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think of the voice command?
It is appreciated, but isn’t it overestimated?
It cannot be said that it is the panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because we do not always want to inform others of their actions or intentions.
In fact, every type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its niche.
For example, in order to control the devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discreet, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera of the device, but by a hand-carried bracelet that recorded the movements of bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to give you this can?
You would do it with speech and gestures.
- Usually, I'm just talking.
- Oh, it's gonna be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt according to what the machine can or can't do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but this is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, they produce a fairly good resolution in depth and this is very important.
- If we're interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what do you don't like about modern cameras?
Are they lacking resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, it is the current generation that we rely on in our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be nice to get about 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and depth.
Compared to this last point, all current technologies are quite good, this adds work to the algorithm designers.
It is necessary to keep in mind the resolution according to the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche of our Redmond lab gave the touch of the sensors a regular processing delay of between 1 and 100 <0xCE><0xBC>s, with the current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a device of this type in my work, but I don't need to touch, to have more frames at the second.
Shouldn’t we increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second, a reflected signal receiver.
And the third camera is actually a usual visible field sensor.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
Many cameras could solve this problem...
Or worsen it by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a flexible product similar to the Kinect, to play with the curve of the cameras and see how it could help define the locations.
As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that from a point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the platforms with the most perspectives?
- Of course, walking all the time with a smartphone with your hands up is not practical but here is what I think: the best option would be a "transitory" augmented reality that would allow you to switch from a cloud platform to the smartphone.
Glasses are a very personal device and that is what makes their strength (the personal elements are those that you are the only one to see) and at the same time their weakness: augmented reality from glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the mere mortal.
There is a problem that opponents of this idea point to: there is no tactile sensation!
The hands feel nothing!
What answers is your group preparing for this challenge?
In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth might very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
At the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as an image medium.
It perfectly records the pressures!
But there are also technologies that are really meant to assign palpability to these "images in the air": for example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed to a specific point where the finger is located and which gives you the feeling, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of your fingers.
There are also wrist straps that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a working axis with perspectives.
- And you tried to fool the brain?
To make him believe that he feels what he should normally feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried yet.
There is still one task underneath which it will take a long time to struggle: the way to make someone who is physically in a very small space believe that they are walking in an almost infinite open space - we are working on the concepts of treadmills (not to do with those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
At the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain, there is still many years of work.
This is what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: many things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
