Birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Caravans of space shuttles with Earthlings on board go in search of a planet of rescue.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how can we continue to live our species in weightlessness or on a planet of relief?
I don't think there's much of a choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
“It’s about Venus and Mars,” says Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If on Mars the conditions are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500.
We can only live there at very high altitude or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on flora.
Half a century ago, we were experimenting on plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from Earth varieties.
Then insects, small breeding drosophile flies, were put into orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how an embryo developed in weightlessness.
At the exit, we get a completely normal chick.
It is then that the problems begin.
"The problem is related to the fact that the chick has to find a support, he has to get on his feet and start moving," explains the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
Unable to find any support, the chicks agitated disorderly.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
“We shot them twice and then gave up because it’s simply impossible to work with them there,” Sychev said, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological “miniature ark” with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, biosatellite "Bion" will only ship species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. You have to do this kind of research," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
Nonetheless, it is not yet possible to make reproductions directly in space.
It's not a small business.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike beasts, man is able to do so, in principle.
Homo sapiens possesses abstract thought, it is capable of creating a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
Women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the feminine organism is the most precious thing humanity has.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would stand after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the flight.
“Nobody answered that question,” says Vakhtang Vatchnadzé, a retired rocket and space sector officer.
In June 1964, just a year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a little girl.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, having been in orbit twice and even worked in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it poses a danger even during flights in orbit," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet humanity must look for new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
Hydrology laboratory of the Cosmonaut Preparation Centre: mandatory stage of flight preparation.
Here, in zero buoyancy, the cosmonauts train to extra-vehicular exits.
Water imitates weightlessness.
If for adults, water is comfortable but nevertheless a foreign environment, for infants, it is their real element.
Small amphibious men seem to confirm this: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
Since the baby develops about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid of his mother's womb, it is easier for him to get used to water afterwards.
This is logical in principle, because from his birth to his first bath, it takes only 2 weeks.
"It's very little to forget," explains infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the newly born child weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravity, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, pelvis atrophy very quickly, the baby's ability to push is lost.
All right, let's ignore that by relying on the birth simulators.
Of course, you can prepare a childbirth in a special room, the woman will manage to get him out.
"What then?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to invite us to reflect on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
If it does not feel the terrestrial attraction, the body does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
One cannot dress an infant like an adult with a special suit for training.
It will simply be deprived of its vital needs.
"And this experience that we would consider in this case, imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the return to Earth of a disabled child, who is completely disappointed," predicts the Director of the Bioethics Committee of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
The birth of children in space is still a matter of theory.
However, over time this will become a reality, when the Earthlings will travel on their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their space-born offspring.
The head of the ISC (Superior Institution of Control of Public Finance) said: "the control of pseudo-self-employment (in Czech " <0xC5><0xA0>varc system") has failed because of the politicians.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation, but it lags behind in its application.
