A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
As an example of abusive practice, he cites Petr Ne<0xC4><0x8D>as' approach to the " <0xC5><0xA0>varc system".
The Prime Minister recently stated that the SDG would not bother contractors with controls; is it allowed or prohibited?
"The law must be applied in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government can't stop an authority to go and inspect to demand compliance with the law," Kala said.
At the control committee meeting in the Chamber of Deputies, you mentioned a Czech-German project in which the procurement laws of these two countries were compared.
What was it really about?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation and a proper practice follow it.
We have put all this together and although this control procedure has not yet been completed, some very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation may be "strenger and better", however, according to some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This therefore confirms that it is not sufficient to continuously develop more and more detailed rules, but that it is necessary to devote itself to the application of the law itself.
How can this project help you concretely and what results for you?
A common control of this kind should help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when this does not really have a positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But by lowering the market thresholds, this goal will not necessarily be achieved.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those looking for its flaws will find far more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems regarding the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our ISC or a different way of organizing?
As for the institutions, similarly to the ISC, the Bundesrechnungshof operates there, which is organised similarly, it also has a council constituted a little differently, but these two institutions proceed basically in a similar way .
The competences are also, to a certain extent, similar, but with a nuance in relation to our system: Germany being a federal structure, it therefore also has audits of this type at the level of the various Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which at home corresponds to state resources.
The public funds managed by the regions and municipalities in our country are checked at the level of the Länder's auditors.
When it comes to national legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model, but it certainly cannot be said that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better inspectors?
No, certainly not, but I repeat, I do not have comparative data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we see as a model, is also facing a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they would have no advantage of cooperating with our institution, would they?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has the amendment of the Public Procurement Act meant to you as an institution? Are its effects already felt?
As this amendment entered into force relatively recently, it has not yet had an impact on our control operations.
As we do checks a posteriori, we have to count on a certain delay.
Our observations concern, for the moment, only the process of preparing for future controls - we have launched a new "risk of mismanagement" instrument with which we have screened nearly 14,000 public contracts - these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been amended and the conditions for certain types of tendering procedures and so on.
So do you see the adoption of this law as an advantage or an additional burden for the administration?
I believe that this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that may arise is that these rules become more stringent and that it is not possible to comply with them.
Already under the previous regulations, the claimant (e.g., the Regional Council, in the case of regional operational programmes) compelled the controlled subjects to accept that any breach of the market law constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really useful to make the law tougher in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who make formal errors without impact on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the prime minister said that the SDG was not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA0>varc system – what does that mean?
Is the <0xC5><0xA0>varc system prohibited or allowed?
