Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of ESA projects.
However, the route from Poland to space began much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles were working on spaceflight; they did not always find understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture of A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
The said Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagandist of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of the world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
In 1925 a draisine was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the drasine.
The only known information about this draisine is that of the press at the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is clear from the documents retained that this research had reached the stage of testing.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric rocket, drawn by engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were conducted by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronautical society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company was mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Probême, which contained four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these papers, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and as early as autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed just under 5 kg.
An improved version, RM-1A, was subsequently built and, in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage rocket RM-2 were begun in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and weighed probably 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was halted.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautics Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision has raised a strong debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberalist-oriented economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means that the different economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (wage) create a strain on prices.
Under this term, the following meaning must be used: a producer endeavours by importing goods sold at low prices to withstand economic competition by "making" the price of the competitor more expensive, with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increasing his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, buying at low prices, or disappearing. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, the social burdens of the State necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so publicly known that there is no need to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital into their homes.
In other words, governments place their own population at the mercy of private capital without regard to social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to force its own population economically to accept the price diktat of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is due on the one hand to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other hand to the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour legislation.
The result is increasing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In Germany, for years there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of these people is already counted by millions.
In the context of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay an additional fee to reach the vital minimum.
Such a scandal has been updated, for example, in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the southern EU member states undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced to either emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), or to live with miserable wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day their country will invest in private capital.
We have to ask ourselves the question: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or else a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media say, to get tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the managed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and even today, according to its own selfish interests, govern politics and by it the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby present in all States.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the development of bills to law firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills were then passed in the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as Western constitutions state, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberalist democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book "The Crisis of the Roman Empire at the time of Caesar and Pompeii": "The state was long in decline and functions were attributed by violence.
The bribes, the favors obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The under-tables and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold"...... "The honest people did not seek to obtain functions at all, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls".... ' It was really said that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy and that it was necessary to choose a man in the ésic.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, today's society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard to the interest of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and asserting the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is a decadence without precedent of the elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore seek the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future losses of human lives, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and internally, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investment in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
