The movie Argo: When everything goes badly, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamist students stormed the American embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, abandon the Shah, because it would have severely shaken the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
This was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed heavily to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated expeditions, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through a rocky cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a filming team who came to search for a major science fiction film.
Combination of genders
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan demanded Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is part of a realistically designed political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, a betrayal - as, for example, in the Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
The atmospheres follow each other: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the era of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
A ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting has ceased to elicit ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It is also the first film by Affleck that does not take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo, where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake shooting crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that actually offered few exciting scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
He does very well, he sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is dismissed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing strip is quite pulled by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their roles as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have earned a bigger place and they are not, far from, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it shows itself with moderate interest, enjoying the realization and retro style of the 1970s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a history still, in some way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the job.
