The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual public inquiry into the most absurd banking fees, has now decided to launch the contest of the regulation or ideas from the most absurd "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU has recently been considering adopting a 40 percent quota of women for the management of large European companies has been at the root of our decision," Patrik Nacher, the organizer of the survey, told the Právo newspaper.
Among the absurdities mentioned is already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women have benefited from life insurance rates because they objectively pose a lower risk to insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of the "EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013," Nacher said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the obligation to add organic components to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the prohibition of the use of reliable mercury thermometers, solely because they contain a relatively small amount of a hazardous substance, or the Directive on the size of chicken cages, which has led to the increase in the price of chicken cages.
Criticism has also been expressed in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the term "spatting butter" or the withdrawal of the sale of conventional bulbs.
Quality bananas must be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or group of states (so the Czech Republic is currently imposing demands from its banks by threatening to use its right of veto).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, at the root of the fact that in the Union bananas must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an "abnormal curvature".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was only harmonizing non-homogeneous national standards that complicated trade.
Standards for fruit and vegetables have been eased despite opposition from some States, claiming that the existing directives result in food waste.
The first prize may be awarded in this survey to last year's EU regulation that must include on inflatable balloons a warning that children under the age of 8 should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU has referred to an American survey according to which balloons are, among toys, the leading cause of death of children by choking.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when it comes to blowing in fair trumpets.
We also have weird ideas.
