The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that true adventures are not just about imagination. To convince yourself, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large neighboring company, tells us: "Yes, this building is indeed very beautiful."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the internet, an iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, no one willingly goes to any of these fiddly libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather peculiar record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty small miniatures of painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
Thus the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam MVRDV architects’ office, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of spirited and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual flame and presented himself at the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a laugh on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, bewildered and shrugging their shoulders, Maas stacked his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech backed by activist arguments with a: "Common dear!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30-million-euro mountain sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and semi-detached houses for a total of 50 houses.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus this dull little village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of awe-inspiring ugliness, whose white facades invite us to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Of course, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you walk the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant street lights speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
People are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing balls.
And everywhere books, books and books.
"Normally, the library shelves are located along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," explains Willy Maas.
We completely upset the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been aptly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical power station of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panels, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircases.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened building architects and engineers do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, said in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in a Frisian farming company an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, the one millimeter thick synthetic membrane has been used as a substrate in greenhouses and fields for years.
It's cheap and you save time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal humidity level of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology," Trouborst said.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only lights up for a short time inside, even on days of good weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted transversely with respect to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade serve as a sun screen, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "finally found soul."
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the voids of the library that was not yet completely filled (today, it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
According to architect Winy Maas, “there is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has achieved the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though it may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against Palestinians’ request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
What's wrong with that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not too critical of Israel.
In the March 2011 Libyan uprising, Germany also chose to abstain from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore clashed on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find this role, but they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Britain
What does the term “normal” foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national cases.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to clash with public opinion, but also with the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
However, I would not place too much emphasis on this, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is, at any rate, a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain from major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I think the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan issue.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions about the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
The United States has vetoed with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly shows a great deal of understanding for the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, of course, the government cannot defend its position publicly.
I believe that the true differences of opinion are not so great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu’s policy.
Is Germany struggling to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I don't think it's easy for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They therefore cannot be part of a broader political line and must affirm their singular position.
This is what they are doing now in the euro issue.
In my view, in the future, Germany will take on a locomotive role and push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been a delicate one.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, does Germany only want to take on a key role?
Or is it still having a hard time taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still struggling to play a more important role.
If, for example, we look at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German sentiments are heard.
