"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo...what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, he's not sure she would win the case.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a firm specializing in property rights violations in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few additional letters to register their trademarks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, Lu-Gucci is recorded, and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is recorded.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a workbook containing registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by taking part of the name Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and infringing intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually only counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are different: his contenders charge him to tackle the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a denomination that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
This is the term for women who marry rich men.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend," Pattloch said.
"The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to the reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs amount to millions for the sectors concerned, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to data from market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of 15 billion euros, the world’s third largest luxury product market and the fastest growing.
However, it is not easy to delete dubious registrations from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports on the trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long time, the denomination criticized had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist because it would have hurt his brand in China.
In this area, sometimes the law of the jungle dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machine manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought the concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the buyer of Volvo, used a blue-and-white logo reminiscent of that of BMW, and the dispute was resolved and Geely had to change it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost to plagiarists in Hong Kong and Singapore who had redirected the famous crocodile’s gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
However, the CTMO brand office in Beijing admits that it experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, last year, the office reportedly went from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a restored normality".
Thus, the number of untreated opposition proceedings would have fallen by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were reported to have been closed, an increase of 75% compared to the previous year.
Nonetheless, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the Office.
Acting is expensive
As is often the case in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, the OTC received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, nearly a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and this means that China is at the top of the ranking for the tenth consecutive time for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office reportedly accounted for 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each record averaged 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been battling a Chinese plagiarist.
Of course, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault because surnames cannot be protected in Germany,” said Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The Trademark Office therefore rejected the objection of the Munichers.
Freudenberg has won in the following two instances, but the opposing party continues to fight to this day.
Vigilance is a must
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nonetheless, he adds: "The procedure is lengthy, time-consuming and costing us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs, and the Archives Department has even had to review the events of the past 100 years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even offered the opposing party in vain a “large six-digit euro sum” to settle the dispute.
“That’s how we see what it means to us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to overflow into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators from this region were to ensure the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file in Germany the name Freudenberg for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it had still been able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "Vigilance is a must."
Pattloch and he advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, they say, to rely on international trademark law, foreigners should instead "register also in China everything that is likely to be protected," as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs can be much higher than those of the registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of its legal drama, the company would have to pay license fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the market segment in question.
