The Rakfisk of Norway: Is it the most odorous fish in the world?
The five million people who inhabit Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be linked to the appetite of the locals for an extremely smelly fish?
Take some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty football clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of the most popular foods in Norway.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this ubiquitous smell permeates the air.
Rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When the darkness sets in and it is cold, Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival that takes place here in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
"You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavite," explains Havard Halvarsen, a local full-time firefighter who is also known as "Rakfisk General", responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavite to rakfisk,” adds Havard.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid getting it under your nose, it’s not bad – it reminds you of sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
Rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, fish was immersed in airtight water barrels and then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - undoubtedly with the senses diminished by alcohol - ate.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, mainly emigrating to the United States.
Now, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted to full employment, high wages and a complete health care system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
Rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital, albeit fragrant, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 € each.
Norway does not often talk about it in international news, which is not displeasing to it.
People here are not willing to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing extremist racist who shot down 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they talk about the "July 22 incident."
The Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country, one of their own could have committed such a barbaric act.
Since the early 1970s, Norway has owed its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
“But oil isn’t the only reason that justifies our success,” explains Anna, our waitress, with blond hair and eyes of a piercing blue, the image of Nordic well-being, with a rakfisk tray in her hand.
We are, as you say, prudent people.
His English, like that of most people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything, with the exception of a small percentage of money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries threw money out of the windows, during the years leading to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep the cords of its stock market tight.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we are happy," Anna says.
"Not to mention the rakfisk," she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand under the snow and queue to buy myself food - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a hamburger made up of momentum, a real discovery, is excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I stay in is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where you can vote for the best of them - or perhaps the most smelly of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter wears a butterfly knot, surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
It looks like the Eurovision competition.
"What score did you give the best fish in the Thor-Juergen mountains?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of aquavite abuse.
Or maybe it's because of the fish emanations.
