Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood are cousins of Hamas, and their leaders are more easily relying on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas may emerge as an important player that cannot be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, supporters of Israel’s hard line will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been boxed again.
The missile interception system called Iron Dome has proven its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will be able to sleep on both ears - for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America renews its unwavering support; and many European countries have blamed Hamas for being the source of the latest wave of violence.
But most importantly, Israel prospered, especially under Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who completely ignored the peace process.
Although rocket fire from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared suicide bombings, notably thanks to the separation barrier encroaching on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and protecting Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite their illegality under international law.
Netanyahu, whose Likud party has merged with an even more warlike party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, has the beautiful part.
Why spoil these fucking Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they were to lead the West Bank, wouldn’t they launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind this wall and hit them as soon as they come out of the head.
