Back in the White House, he seems equally reluctant to establish one.
This is a very narrow vision.
The stability of the Middle East is a vital issue for America.
This involves a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Laws for neutral cigarette packages have come into force in Australia
Warnings and pictures of sick organs cover the dark green packets which are all identical, regardless of brand
This law entered into force in Australia is a world first, logos and colors have been replaced by dark olive green and horrible photos of sick organs and depictions of children and babies whose diseases were caused by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since this Saturday, is the brand name, printed in fine print on all the packages.
It is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government said the goal was to deter young people from smoking by removing any glamorous representation.
Studies have shown that if people did not start smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never start.
"Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image," said federal health minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have revealed, for example, that children associated the crown of a logo with a princess.
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has pushed against this law.
Tobacco makers said it would boost black market trade, which will make it easier to access cheaper cigarettes.
“Negative consequences will arise from this legislation,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others said the law had boosted their activity.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said demand for cigarette cases, including silicone to mask the horrific packaging, has risen sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost in Australia's high court.
Ha said Zico has sold 6,000 of them to wholesalers and is awaiting stock renewal.
For us, business is good.
The only boredom, experts say, is the popularity of social media and the slice of population targeted by the plan.
After a series of Australian laws banning TV ads, sports sponsorship and the obligation for resellers to hide cigarettes, tobacco marketing is now available online.
