The problem is that it has been defined, and debated, in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After scrolling through numerous publications and submitting the idea to a discussion group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience that consists of "wanting to do something but failing to embark on a satisfactory activity."
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task even though he would like it.
With apathy, he says, there is no desire to do anything.
What is at the heart of the boredom, he said, is "the interruption of the attention process, associated with a bad mood and the feeling that time passes slowly."
Boredom can strongly resemble depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while the two can be related, people who get bored tend to think that the problem comes from the environment or the world, while depressed people think that the problem comes from them.
Sometimes we think that we are bored when it is actually a problem of concentration.
As part of their study, “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” which was published in the journal “Perspectives on Psychological Science” in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an earlier experiment in which participants listened on cassette, the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard, from the room next door, the too high sound of a TV show that had no relation, others just heard the TV show, and the third group didn't hear the soundtrack at all.
Those who heard low-noise TV said they were more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but didn't know why, and attributed this focus problem to boredom.
When you try to focus on a difficult or staking task, an interruption of attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
