The hardest job in the world: human mules by Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living carrying the sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It has to work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the earth's entrails solidifies in contact with air.
After harvesting large rocks of sulphur, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a tortoise pace, keeping balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a mistake could cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company has installed a little below at 1,850 meters altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, we can say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in daily life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per trip," explains Anto, who usually travels three times a day.
Each takes him 3 hours and he ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is triple what he would earn in the fields.
“The miners’ income is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the bearer who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned close to his family to Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as the sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindu's, and I've been to the Java's.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life challenging the danger on the Kawah Ljen, but the sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill despite covering his face with a mask and wearing special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
“I’m going to work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,” he promises in a more than acceptable English language.
Strangled by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the job of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wooden masure with other wearers, gets up every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur does not stop pouring out at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the midst of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater lighting up with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they also do not receive a sub of 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) per camera surcharge, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not humans,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent wearer who has been working at Kawah Ijen for thirty years since he left college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18 years.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, 53, can only carry 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which three trucks carry to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away, via a goat trail invaded by weeds.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life,” Unainik says, opening his mouth well, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult jobs in the world: the human mules of the Kawah Ljen volcano.
Singapore seeks babies to save the economy
Singaporeans throw responsibility for this lack of children on the career, stress and cost of access to property.
“Singapore’s population needs to grow.”
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, do our civic duty and give your life!
It may seem unlikely that these words come from an advertisement for mint pellets, but despite that, or perhaps thanks to that, the video spread like a dust slice on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references such as "Let's put a chicken in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the issue in a fun way through this advertisement.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill “their national duty.”
It is intended only for the Internet, so we were able to make it entertaining and fun.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth, so we felt it was a theme we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things like throwing pheromone perfumes or organizing speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we said to ourselves: what could be more creative to solve this problem than making it a rap song?
1.2 children
The government of Singapore does not take it so lightly.
He spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage his citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favor of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its leaders’ conservatism and strict social controls.
The birth rate of Singapore, according to its national population distribution, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
Why do Singaporeans not have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy for the National Population Division, says it’s due to “better education” and “wider choice of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and building a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms contributed to the increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
In the meantime, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter the decline in population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound in scarcely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese people who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in place in Singapore experienced its worst election results since independence last year.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a country’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, it started to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoeboxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of real estate company EL Developers, says its “shoeboxes” sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these dwellings are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously put sticks in the wheels if they wanted to offer too many small housing units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If so much of these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the center, it would seem that they will not have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that’s why people put it off,” says a young executive.
Other people may have children.
“But for me, it’s important to be able to have my money and my time,” another 20-year-old told us.
Men and women mention their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as reasons preventing them from having children.
So, although the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is Singaporeans themselves who have the last word.
