UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the United Nations, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be leaked after the close of the summit, and then claimed that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government's website.
When questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief press statements.
Journalists' access to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, limited audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulated among the journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit of South America and Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, although this was promptly requested by the press, it had also not disseminated the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the obtaining of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that settles a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear the pleas of both parties in Lima’s trial against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing today before this international court," President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals," President Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era said, shaking hands with President Humala, alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
He read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He said actions would be put in place to improve “cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for improved accessibility to medicines, cheap access to the Internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters.”
With Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphant matrix but should help increase our productive matrix and envision a better future for our populations,” concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to favour a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were pertaining to Peru and were on the transverse axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours, is another topic discussed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all of these pathways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with this country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to witness the takeover of the new president of the country, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
Similarly, within the framework of the summit, the bloc’s defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of the UNASUR, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the pro-tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
