Moreover, the Ecuadorian president considers the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of The Hague, which will strengthen the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua.
At the moment, this judgment is not respected.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the willingness to move forward together.
We need to solve them as a whole to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the proper resolution of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile in the same court and affirmed that it is "beneficial for Latin America to take international proceedings if the two countries agree to accept a judgment as firm as it may be."
Referring to the possibility of his presentation as a candidate for the upcoming presidential elections in Ecuador, with a view to running for a third consecutive term, he noted that he saw this possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 primaries, he would withdraw from public life.
On a personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as those in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be solved through political power.
“My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this eventual victory, but we have to accept that responsibility,” he said.
If I won, that would be my last presidential term and then I’ll retire from politics.
If we lose, I will too.
“That’s my decision,” he said.
Correa also referred to Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez’s new medical treatment in Cuba.
I just talked with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
“This does not mean a relapse of President Chávez’s state of health,” he said.
