The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to find out about him and his fierceness was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the civilian hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), in which he ended up in 1994 after numerous battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, little choice of treatment and more stigma.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "depleted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first cases reported, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the appropriate time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva.
Infectionist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS rates were no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depended on the level of immune system allocation patients presented at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those not using drugs up to a rate of 200 years:
To put it simply, it means that for someone who gets a positive HIV diagnosis at age 25, “as long as he remains under control, he will be able to live without problems up to 75 years,” the scientist said.
In order to put this progress in its context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of AIDS-related deaths has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients identified on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I think the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
In the last 12 years at least, we have never missed medication, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or else they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
“Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, we must offer screening tests in a massive way, to all those who ask for it.”
Specialists and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do the patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he was already a carrier of AIDS and suffered from a can't of Ka's disease.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they’re going to die and don’t want to know anything.
“If I’m going to die, it’s better if I’m going to burst three times a week,” they say, not me.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medications.
To date, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
