There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest thing is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "the distribution of condoms was actually increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packets of a hundred, that's fine, but as a result, even today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", posed with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, says the journalist.
It proposes to redirect this ineffective distribution; that condoms not only be sold at the counters, but that they be found in the distributors of public toilets and in places that young people frequent.
This is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had replied when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
"It's not how sexuality works, it's best to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active," he said.
Numbers in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The State is the 4th state in the country in the number of new cases and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th for the number of HIV patients.
92% of contaminations are sexual, 6% are blood and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for each recorded case there are 4 or 5 people who are unaware of it.
A judgment ratified by a U.S. court on appeal ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group's debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, which sets a precedent for all domestic companies with branches in the neighboring country and with solvency problems.
It seems, therefore, that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star banner, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the June 15 ruling by Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenseless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s leading glass manufacturer to sue the U.S. Supreme Court on the basis of three inconsistencies.
First, while the case judge points out that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal, sitting in New Orleans, asserts that the main proceeding is formalized business bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the inter-company vote, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro's subsidiaries to the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, the case of Vitro is not the first to use this plan.
There are half a dozen examples here, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
In addition, what is certain is that, since there were still the votes of the subsidiaries, in any way the Vitro creditors who fought against this in the United States courts, that is, the "vautour" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have won the majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
A fact that was omitted by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro has been blamed for the difficult situation it has been in since 2008 without stopping the severe economic crisis facing the United States, which has remitted costs to the country.
